  "texts": [
    "Figure [7].d reports the speedup of different P2P interaction types (local, remote, periodic) in the Redundant implementation, showing how remote and periodic computations slow down by increase in density.",
    "Figure [7].e breaks down the speedup of individual P2P components (collection, transfer, compute, update) and shows that the kernel computations reaches to 3X faster in Redundant implementation for t=8 (default value) and always faster than Indexing implementation also the update process which is faster because of its data volume.",
    "The Indexing implementation consume larger memory volume due to its padding scheme and the non-uniform particle distribution.",
    "That the P2P speedup for Redundant implementation raises from 0.55X for t=2 to 0.9X for t=32 and drops to 0.81X for t=64 as depicted in Figure [7].f.The overall applications speedup grows gradually from 0.79X for t=2 to 0.98X for t=32 and drops to 0.94X for t=64 which is better than the P2P speedup rooted in reduced share of P2P in overall runtime.",
    "Local Computation Shows High Kernel Speedup according to Figure [7].d the most significant performance gain is observed in local P2P computations, where data redundancy improves spatial locality and reduces cache misses."
  ],
